<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is DNS?", answer: "The Domain Name System (DNS) is a hierarchical, distributed naming system that translates human-readable domain names like example.com into IP addresses like 93.184.216.34 that computers use to identify each other on the network. DNS acts as the phone book of the internet. When you type a URL into your browser, a DNS resolver queries a chain of authoritative name servers to find the IP address associated with that domain." },
  { question: "What are the different DNS record types?", answer: "The most common DNS record types are: A records map a domain to an IPv4 address, AAAA records map to an IPv6 address, MX records specify mail servers for the domain, TXT records hold arbitrary text data often used for email authentication (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) and domain verification, CNAME records create aliases pointing one domain name to another, NS records identify the authoritative name servers for a domain, and SOA records contain administrative information about the DNS zone including the primary nameserver and zone serial number." },
  { question: "What is TTL in DNS?", answer: "TTL (Time To Live) is a value in seconds that tells DNS resolvers how long to cache a DNS record before requesting a fresh copy from the authoritative server. A low TTL (e.g., 300 seconds / 5 minutes) means records update quickly but generate more DNS traffic. A high TTL (e.g., 86400 seconds / 24 hours) reduces DNS queries but means changes take longer to propagate. When migrating servers, administrators often lower TTL in advance so the transition happens faster." },
  { question: "What is DNS-over-HTTPS?", answer: "DNS-over-HTTPS (DoH) sends DNS queries through encrypted HTTPS connections instead of plain-text UDP. This prevents ISPs, network operators, and attackers from seeing or tampering with your DNS queries. Google Public DNS (dns.google), Cloudflare (1.1.1.1), and other providers offer DoH endpoints. Major browsers now support DoH natively. This tool uses Google's DoH API to perform lookups." },
  { question: "What does NXDOMAIN mean?", answer: "NXDOMAIN (Non-Existent Domain) is a DNS response code indicating that the queried domain name does not exist in the DNS system. This typically means the domain has not been registered, has expired, or is misspelled. It is different from NOERROR with empty answers, which means the domain exists but has no records of the requested type." }
]) %>

